March 9 Tutorial: Introduction to tidyverse and ggplot

In this class we introduced the tidyverse and ggplot packages. For this tutorial both the music and lego datsets were used. We first looked at how to load the packages into r using the library() function, and then talked about filtering data and making some (gorgeous) plots. Code is shown below. (Also note Ive broken this into two code chunks where the output for loading packages is hidden)

#### USING THE MUSIC DATASET
music <- read.csv('Datasets/spotify.csv')
lego <- read.csv('Datasets/lego.csv')

#### Filtering data 
music %>% filter(danceability>.5) %>% ggplot(aes(x=danceability)) + 
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

lego %>% ggplot(aes(x=Price, y=rating)) + geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'
## Warning: Removed 1775 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 1775 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

music %>% ggplot(aes(y=danceability))+geom_boxplot()

music %>% filter(artists=="['Justin Bieber']" | artists=="['Eminem']") %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=danceability, col=artists))+geom_boxplot()
